<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="86" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="86">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="9" pageNumber="86">
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Macrocheilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Macrocheilus gigas" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gigas">Macrocheilus gigas</taxonomicName>
is similar to 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Macrocheilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Macrocheilus parvimaculatus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="parvimaculatus">Macrocheilus parvimaculatus</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Macrocheilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Macrocheilus tripustulatus" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tripustulatus">Macrocheilus tripustulatus</taxonomicName>
in having anterior seta of the labrum on the apical margin and the ligula thickened at apex which distinguishes these three species from other species with two spots on each elytron. But 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Carabidae" genus="Macrocheilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Macrocheilus gigas" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="86" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gigas">Macrocheilus gigas</taxonomicName>
differs from the other two species by wide apex of labrum and having median tooth of mentum sinuate near apex on lateral margin.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
